## 🎯 Language-Specific Considerations

### Japanese (日本語)
**Challenges:**
- Very long text in narrow spaces
- Multiple character sets (Hiragana, Katakana, Kanji)
- Cultural terminology specific to Japanese gaming

**Testing Focus:**
- [ ] Text overflow in UI elements
- [ ] Font supports all three character sets
- [ ] Terminology consistent with Japanese gaming conventions

### Spanish (Español)
**Challenges:**
- Regional differences (Spain vs. Latin America)
- Accented characters (á, é, í, ó, ú, ñ)
- Formal vs. informal speech variations

**Testing Focus:**
- [ ] Consistent terminology across regions
- [ ] Accented characters display correctly
- [ ] Regional dialect consistency if specified

### French (Français)
**Challenges:**
- Complex grammar and longer words than English
- Accented characters (é, è, ê, ë, à, ù, ü, ö, ç)
- French UI conventions (spacing before punctuation)

**Testing Focus:**
- [ ] Text field width accommodates longer words
- [ ] Accented characters render properly
- [ ] Proper spacing before punctuation marks

### German (Deutsch)
**Challenges:**
- Very long compound words
- Umlaut characters (ä, ö, ü, ß)
- Gender-specific terminology

**Testing Focus:**
- [ ] UI accommodates long German words
- [ ] Umlaut characters display correctly
- [ ] Terminology remains clear despite length

### Portuguese (Português)
**Challenges:**
- Regional differences (Brazil vs. Portugal)
- Cedilla character (ç)
- Different vocabulary between regions

**Testing Focus:**
- [ ] Brazilian vs. European Portuguese consistency
- [ ] Cedilla and accent characters render
- [ ] Regional terminology appropriate for target market

### Chinese (Simplified & Traditional)
**Challenges:**
- Large character sets
- Line breaking for CJK text
- Punctuation differs from Western languages

**Testing Focus:**
- [ ] Font supports full character set
- [ ] Line breaks occur at appropriate points
- [ ] Punctuation displays correctly

